For backwards compatibility reasons, a DDL statement should not
implicitly start a transaction. This code achieves that.

Closes #59.
Closes #21.
Fixes #24.
Closes #80.

Completety got rid of statement parsing. We now use SQLite functions to
determine if a statement modifies the database or not. If a statement
modifies the database, then we implicitly start a transaction. This also
means that DDL statements like CREATE TABLE now start transactions.

This is not 100% backwards compatible, but the fix is easy: add commit()
calls to your code after DDL statements. On older pysqlite releases and
when using the sqlite3 module from the standard library, adding the
commit() doesn't hurt.
Remove SQLite version checks for obsolete SQLite releases.
Remove unused import.

Use sqlite3_get_autocommit() to determine if we are within a
transaction instead of trying to be smart.
